<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>The London Cycling Campaign is a charity with nearly 12,000 members</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; font-weight:bold">7</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">/</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; font-weight:bold">8</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:18pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 5pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from the London Cycling Campaign (CYS0071)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">              </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The London Cycling Campaign welcomes the opportunity to contribute to th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">e Transport Select Committee’s follow up</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> inquiry into cycling. We share the committee’s concern at the tragic death of 6 people in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">just two weeks on London roads.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> The continued growth of cycling in London and the UK must be accompanied, and assisted by, a reduction of road danger to cycle users </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">and pedestrians</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.58pt; padding-left:8.42pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Road danger is the number one concern for quarter of the population who would like to cycle or cycle more</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.58pt; padding-left:8.42pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Providing safe and convenient passage through </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">busy </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">ju</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">nctions and along main roads requires, as in the Netherlands, separatio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">n in time or space of cyclists from motor traffic </span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.58pt; padding-left:8.42pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Motor traffic capacity must not be prioritised over </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">safety of vulnerable road users</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.58pt; padding-left:8.42pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Cycle training must be incorporated in the school curriculum</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.58pt; padding-left:8.42pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Road schemes must consider cycle users from the outset</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.58pt; padding-left:8.42pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">nternational </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">best practice in road design </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">must be incorporated in UK guidance</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.58pt; padding-left:8.42pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Spending on cycling infrastructure must match the levels on the continent</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.58pt; padding-left:8.42pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">All public bodies must adopt procurement policies that require safer lorries and trained drivers </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">London Cycling Campaign</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">he London Cycling Campaign is a charity </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">with more than 4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">0,000 supporters of who</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">12,000 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">are full </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">members. We </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">speak up on behalf of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> everyone who cycles, or want</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> to cycle, in Greater London. Our aim is for London to be a world</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">class cycling city. Founded in 1978, our organisation campaigns for every street in the city to be cycle</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">friendly so</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> millions more Londoners</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, whatever the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ir</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> age or ability,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> can enjoy the benefits of cycling, helping to creat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">e a cleaner, healthier and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">less </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">congested capital.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">LCC, and its 33 local groups, regularly respond to planning consultations, inquiries into cycling and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">provide</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> informed input to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">policy making at both the local </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">and London-wide-levels. Our input and lobbying work led to the comprehe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">nsive revision of London’s cycling programmes now encapsulated in the Mayor’s Vision for Cycling in London. While the LCC would like to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> see</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> a significant acceleration in the pace of implementation of the Mayor’s Vision</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, we recognise it</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> as a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">major step</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> towards improving cycling conditions in the capital.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">1.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">reducing road danger</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">1.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Cycle journeys in London have increased by 176% on main roads in the past decade</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and cycle commuting by Hackney residents now accounts for more than 15% of journeys</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> –</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> doubling</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> in a decade.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Yet even the capital, where cycle journeys </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">now exceed 57</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">0,000 per day, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">still has a low o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">verall share of cycling at a little more than </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">2% of all journeys, well below cities like </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Berlin (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">15</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">%) or Amsterdam (36%). </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The overall figure for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> the UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> 2% - significantly below the potential rate. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">1.2 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The key factor in deterring more people from cycling in the UK is road danger and perceived road danger. Recent surveys, both in London</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">and the UK, consistently show that a quarter, or more, o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">f the population would like to cycle or cycle more often. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">urveys carried out for LCC and British Cycling show that the number one factor deterring people from cycling is fear of road danger. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">1.3 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">As the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> funded programme of Cycling Demonstration towns</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> has shown</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> cycling offers an exceptionally cost effective investment in the transport sector. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The Cycling Demonstration Towns showed a cost/benefit ratio of £2- £3.5 for every pound spent and this is described as a conservative </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">estimate</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">A cost</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">/</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">benefit s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">tudy in Copenhagen (a city with high cycling levels) found that the total socio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">economic cost of cycling (including travel time, health factors, pollution and congestion) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">was 0.60 DK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> (Danish Krone</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">) per</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> kilometre compared to 3.74 DK per kilometre for cars</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. </span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Cyclist fatality rates in Holland and Denmark compared to distance travelled are half those in the UK. </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">1.4 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The NICE (National Institute of Clinical Excellence) report on walking cycling, published in December 2012, makes clear that the health cost</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> of an inactive population are enormous and comparable to those of smoking.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">1.5 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">LCC led the Love London Go Dutch campaign in 2012 that secured 42,000 signatures asking the future Mayor to make our roads </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">as safe and inviting for cycling </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">and walking as th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ose in Holland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> The elected Mayor made a commitment to realise this pledge and his response has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">been his</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Vision for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Cycling</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">which commits to both significantly improved infrastructure and safer lorries.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">2. POLITICAL LEADERSHIP</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">2.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">In common with the Tr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">ansport Committee</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> LCC believes that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">political will, within Government and within Local Authorities, is the single most important fundamental and overarching factor that will deliver improved conditions for cycling in the UK, and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">unlock the huge latent </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">demand there is for cycling as an everyday means of transport</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. That political will needs to be reflected in a clear national cycling strategy, backed by adequate resources and funding, which lead to its implementation at local level throughout the country.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">2.2 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">LCC </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">shares the view expressed by the Transport Committee, in its 2012 recommendations on cycling</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> local authorities must work together </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">with central Government </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">to achieve improved cycling conditions and therefore we are seeking to secure the sup</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">port of all local council candidates in the 2014 local elections for cycle-friendly measures in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">London </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">wards.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Our recommendations to candidates. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> These </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">will follow six themes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> all related to reducing road danger and removing barriers to cycling. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="background-color:#d9d9d9; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:462.1pt"><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">2.3 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Space for Cycling 2014 : </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">key themes</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 3pt 27.15pt; padding-left:8.55pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Safe routes for schoolchildren</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 3pt 27.15pt; padding-left:8.55pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Zones</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> with no </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">through motor traffic</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 3pt 27.15pt; padding-left:8.55pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Dedicated space on main roads</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 3pt 27.15pt; padding-left:8.55pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Better greenways</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 3pt 27.15pt; padding-left:8.55pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">20 mph speed limits </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 3pt 27.15pt; padding-left:8.55pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Liveable town centres</span></li></ul></td></tr></table><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">2.4 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">A key element of the process </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">of switching people from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">short </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">car trips (half </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">of which</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">less than</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> 5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> miles </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">UK)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> to walking and cycling </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">is the re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">versal of the policy followed in the 60’s of re-designing cities to enable high-speed motoring. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">f we are to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">achieve the levels of cycling across all demographi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">c groups that are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">seen in the Netherlands</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> then motor traffic must be deprioritised in favour of cycling</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and walking</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> most notably for urban, local journeys</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">2.5 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">This is, at heart, a political rather than a technical matter. To fulfil the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Government’s and Local </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Authorities’ declared</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> commitment to sustainable transport</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, and the numerous environmental, economic and health benefits that follow</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">cycling </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">(and walking) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">must be given </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">priority in both time and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">space over motor traffic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> in the UK’s u</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">rban spaces</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">it is in the Netherlands and Denmark.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> In this context the Government must re-emphasise </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">that the Traffic Management Act must be used to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">prioritise </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">the movement of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">people</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, wherever possible by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">cycling and walking</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ahead of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">the movement of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">motor vehicles</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">A lesson learned in London is that pre-occupation with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">maintaining or increasing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> road capacity for cars can lead highway authorities to overlook, or discard, traffic schemes that can reduce road danger to vulnerable road users and serve to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> encourage walking and cycling. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">Safety Concerns</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">3.1 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Safety concerns are a primary deterrent to cycle use. The factors identified by London r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">oad users include: </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.7pt; padding-left:8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Careless, inattentive driving that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">puts cyclists at risk</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 3pt 27.7pt; padding-left:8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">High speed/high volume motor traffic on roads without </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">dedicated space for cycle users</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:5pt 0pt 3pt 27.7pt; padding-left:8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Road junctions where maximising the flow of motor traffic has been given priority over</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> cyclist and pedestrian safety</span></li></ul><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.15pt; padding-left:8.55pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Large vehicles, especially those ‘off road’ style lor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ries used by the construction industry which lack equipment </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">or large windows that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> make cyclists visible </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 35.7pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="background-color:#d9d9d9; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:462.1pt"><p style="margin:3pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">3.2 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Recommendations</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Every road safety initiative should be re-assessed ensuring that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> it contributes to removing the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">sources of danger to people who </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">cycle and walk</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The road network needs to guarantee safe passage for cyclists by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ensuring clear</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> space at junctions and on main roads</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Traffic violations which consistently put cyclists at risk should be enforced</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> against.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Government and Local</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Authorities sh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ould set rate-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">based targets for casualties to ensure resources are put into effective casualty reduction.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">All Local Authorities should adopt and promote procurement practices to ensure only safe lorry operators are employed by public bodies and their contr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">actors</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> (see HGV section below)</span></li></ul></td></tr></table><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">.  Cycling Infrastructure</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">4.1 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ll urban road infrastructure impacts on the safety of cyclists. The main issues restraining more cycling in London and identified by Londoners </span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> are:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.15pt; padding-left:8.55pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Fear of actual and perceived road danger </span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.15pt; padding-left:8.55pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Lack of confidence in infrastructure </span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#339966; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">4.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Cycle Networks</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">4.3 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">It is evident from successful cycling countries that cycle routes need to build into a network to give people the confidence that they will reach their destination along cycle-friendly roads without encountering major barriers.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">4.4 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">As the Dutch Design M</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">anual for Bic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ycle Traffic (CROW) makes clear</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">cycle networks </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">must offer</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.15pt; padding-left:8.55pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Cohesion</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.15pt; padding-left:8.55pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Directness</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.15pt; padding-left:8.55pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Safety</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.15pt; padding-left:8.55pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Comfort </span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">4.5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">UK cycle networks, whether in London or</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> elsewhere, invariably fall down </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">on some or all of these principles</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> The Mayor of London has announced that a network of ‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Quietways</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">” across London and “Grid” of cycle-friendly streets in central London will build into a network. The quality of such</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">a network</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> must meet continental standards to give people the confidence to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">cycle. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">4.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">6</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Main road network</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> cycle provision</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The level of provision for safe cycling on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">UK main</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> roads</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> remains inadequate.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> London’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Mayor initiate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> a review of major junctions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">following previous</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> deaths,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> in recognition of the problems across the capital</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Cycling infrastructure </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">on main roads </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">is either non-existent or seriously inconveniences cycle journeys</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">n some cases</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> new infrastructure increases risk for cyclists as at recent work on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Henley’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Corner </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">A406</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> This problem is certainly not exclusive t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">o London and must be addressed right across the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">country. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">4.7</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">One Way Road System Removal</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">O</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ne way road </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">systems (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">gyratories</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">) remain one of the biggest barriers to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">both safety and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">increased cycle use</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.  Progress on removing the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">gyratories</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> that blight large parts </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">UK cities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">has been very slow.  A major programme of one way road system removal </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">and the introduction of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">high grade provision for cycle users and walkers is overdue</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">4.8</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Filtered Permeability Measures </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Such schemes allow people on foot or on bikes access through locations where through motor traffic is blocked </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">(often by low cost bollards or a no entry sign) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">for amenity or traffic management reasons. The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">impetus for such s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">chemes often come</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> from residents seeking to eliminate rat running. Permeability schemes such as those in De Beauvoir </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Town,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Hackney </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">and Claremont</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Square,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Islington, attract thousands of cyclists per day (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">up to 1500 per hour - </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">high even by Dutch standards</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">).</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The virtual absence of moving motor vehicles means that collisions are unlikely. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">4.9</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Speed Reduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">In combination with measures such as filtered permeability, speed reduction can create pleasant cycling routes that attract more riders</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> as well as reducing collisions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Following r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ecent changes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> guidance allow</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> 20mph limits on main roads such as the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">TfL</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> network</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, under certain specified conditions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">4.10</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Cycle Superhighways</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The cycle superhighways </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">In London </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">have pro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">vided very visible way marking </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">but they have introduced only a limited number of safety improvements, as acknowledged by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Mayor’s commitment to re-design them with far greater use of mode separation notably at junctions where most collisions occur. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Cy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">cle superhighway 2 in East London is a sad case where six cyclists have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">died in 3 years</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. LCC advised against implementation of this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> highway as originally proposed and welcome</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> the Mayoral commitment to re-design it </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">with protected cycle lanes and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">treated junctions.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">4.11</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Greenways</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ycle paths through Hyde Park and Green Park in central London are highly popular. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Well designed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Greenway routes and links </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">can make </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">a significant impact on improving conditions for both walkers and cyclists. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="background-color:#d9d9d9; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:462.1pt"><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">4.12</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Recommendations</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">All projects on main roads must be designed to continental best practice, providing clear time and space for cyclists of all ages and abilities, and safe passage through junctions at any time of day. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Coherent networks of cycle routes, bui</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">lt, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">waymarked</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and maintained to high standards, must be implemented in all major cities.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">All road designers must be trained in providing infrastructure safe for cycling. Such design guidance must be followed on all roads and not just in cycle schemes. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> should revise its </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Cycle Infrastructure Design </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">guidance to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> include best practice from the continent.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">In residential and shopping areas 20mph limits should be adopted.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">High speed one way road systems should be removed from urban centres</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Programmes of ‘f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">iltered permeability’ improvements should be impleme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">nted in all urban areas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Two way cycling should be facilitated on all minor one way streets and through every motor traffic closure.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">All cycle routes and Greenways must be maintained to a safe standard.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Where high volume cycle routes are built, particular care must be taken with design and reducing the speed and volume of motor traffic should be seen as essential.  Road user safety must take precedence over motor traffic capacity.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Junctions must be design</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ed to minimise road danger for all users not maximise motor traffic throughput.</span></li></ul></td></tr><tr><td style="background-color:#d9d9d9; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:462.1pt"><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">Children &amp; Cycle Training</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">5.1 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Cycling, which enables children to stay active</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and healthy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">needs to be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">incorporated</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> the educational system</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> as it is in the Netherlands</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">5.2 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Incorporating an element of cycle training into the driving test would enable drivers to understand the on-road strategies of cycle users and help reduce the incidence of collisions.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="background-color:#d9d9d9; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:462.1pt"><p style="margin:3pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">5.3 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Recommendations</span></p><p style="margin:3pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:3pt 0pt 0pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">All </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">schoolchildren to have access to cycle training.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">F</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ree or low cost cycle training to be offered to adults.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Schools to be offered combined packages of cycle parking, cycle training and safe routes to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">schools.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Consider including a cycle training element in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">the driving test.</span></li></ul></td></tr></table><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">6</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">  I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">mproving Street Design &amp; Management</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">6.1 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Dutch planners and engineers consider cycle and pedestrian traffic from the outset of any design process.  It is clear that this does not happen in much of the UK.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Consideration of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">‘people’ capacity rather than just motor vehicle capacity would lead to more people friendly planning.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">6.2 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Not all the transport modelling software used by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">TfL</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and other Highway Authorities allows cycle flows as inputs or outputs. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">TfL’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> guidance suggests </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">that junction capacity modelling is unreliable where cycle flows make up 20% </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">(no longer uncommon in London) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">of the traffic flow</span><a name="_ftnref15"></a><a href="#_ftn15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">6.3 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Safety audits must properly consider cycle users. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We note</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, for example</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">TfL</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> guidelines for safety audits of road sc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">hemes do not require auditors to have any detailed knowledge of cycling provision or London Cycle Design Standards</span><a name="_ftnref16"></a><a href="#_ftn16">[16]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="background-color:#d9d9d9; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:462.1pt"><p style="margin:3pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">6.4 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Recommendations</span></p><p style="margin:3pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.75pt; text-indent:-21.75pt"><span style="display:none; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="display:none; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.75pt; text-indent:-21.75pt"><span style="display:none; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="display:none; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 21.75pt; text-indent:-21.75pt"><span style="display:none; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">6.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="display:none; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Cyclist and pedestrian requirements must be considered from the outset in any traffic scheme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Inappropriate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">traffic models should not be used to the detriment of vulnerable road users</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> should </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">organise</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> on a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> ‘Modelling for cycling’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> stakeholder dialogue event.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Safety auditing procedures must ensure competent evaluation of cyclists’ safety.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">7</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">.  Engaging </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">with Cycling Groups</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">7.1 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">DfT’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Cycle Infrastructure Design document</span><a name="_ftnref17"></a><a href="#_ftn17">[17]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> recommend</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">s consultation with user groups</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Cycling groups can provide highway authorities with significant and valuable local input</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> to reduce road danger and improve scheme </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">designs.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="background-color:#d9d9d9; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:462.1pt"><p style="margin:3pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">7.2 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Recommendations</span></p><p style="margin:3pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Consultation with cycle user groups on traffic schemes should be standard practice in line with Government guidance. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Scheme consultation should begin at the pre-design stage to resolve all the cycling related issues.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Stakeholders must be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">approached in good time when consultations take place and their input addressed and responded to. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Consultation should extend to road safety measures, large event organisation and cycling strategies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></li></ul></td></tr></table><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">              </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">8</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">Best National &amp; International Practice</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">8.1 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Best practice from abroad should inform UK planning and design for cycle users. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We provide refe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ren</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ces below. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">TfL</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> recently commissioned an </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">independent </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">study of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">international </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">best practice</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">That forthcoming study notes the following common themes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> in best</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> practice cities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Strong political and technical pro-cycling leadership</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Cycling treated as a major transport mode with investment to match</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Increasing cycle mode share is accompanied by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">decreasing the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> car mode. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Provision of d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">edicated, fit for purpose, space for cycling  free of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">intrusion by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">heavy and fast traffic</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Clarity about the overa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ll cycle network (see CROW above</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">)</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Three types of facility: separate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">facilities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> on busy roads; quiet streets with 20 mph speed limits</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">and restri</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">cted through traffic; ‘greenways’</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Frequency of need for cyclists to stop is minimised</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Cycle safety is not bought at a cost to pedestrians</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and traffic capacity or car parking  are not a veto on cycling provision</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Driving</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> culture is more respectful of cyclin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">g</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Plan for growth in cycling and design accordingly</span><a name="_ftnref18"></a><a href="#_ftn18">[18]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">8.2 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Transport for London </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">and local</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> authorities have complained about </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> restrictions that prevent the adoption of European best practice</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> in road design</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Best practice guides:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.15pt; padding-left:8.55pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">London Cycle Design Stan</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">dards, Transport for London 2013 (forthcoming) </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.15pt; padding-left:8.55pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Manual for Streets, Department for Transport 2007</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.15pt; padding-left:8.55pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Hackney Public Realm Strategy 2012</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.15pt; padding-left:8.55pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Design Manual for Bicycle Traffic, CROW (Netherlands Information and Technology Pl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">atform) 2007 (hard copy only).</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.15pt; padding-left:8.55pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Collecti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">on of Cycle Concepts 2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">012, Cycling Embassy of Denmark.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.15pt; padding-left:8.55pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">NACTO Urban Bikeway Design Guide, NACTO (USA) 2011</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="background-color:#d9d9d9; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:462.1pt"><p style="margin:3pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">8.3 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Recommendations</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Commit to delivering streets designed to best UK and international practice</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Monitor and compare all schemes to ensure </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">compliance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Remove restrictive </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">national </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">regulations that limit designs to 20</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:6.67pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> century concepts.</span></li></ul></td></tr></table><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">9</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">.  SPENDING PRIORITIES</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">9.1 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Cycle </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">use in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> the UK has increased in those towns and cities where funding</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> has been </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">provided –</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> London and the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Demonstration Cycle Towns </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">are the obvious examples. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">9.2 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">he </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Rod </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Eddington</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> report on Transport specifically </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">highl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ighted that investment in cycl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ing offered </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">particular </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">value for money</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">“Improving the attractiveness of walking and cycling, e.g. by creating </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">or upgrading routes, can provide strong returns with wider BCRs (benefit cost ratios) sometimes over 10.”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Eddington’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> conclusion was that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">“some</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> of the best projects are small-scale, such as walking and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">cycling </span><a name="_ftnref19"></a><a href="#_ftn19">[19]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">9.3 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">We note that a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> estimate of the a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">nnual costs of traffic delays, accidents</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> poor air quality</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> physical inactivity, greenhouse gas emissions and noise resulting from motor traffic in urban areas was put at £38 - £48 billion pounds</span><a name="_ftnref20"></a><a href="#_ftn20">[20]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="background-color:#d9d9d9; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:462.1pt"><p style="margin:3pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">9.4 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Recommendations</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Government and Local Authorities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">must allocate resources to make UK roads as safe and inviting for cycling as they are in the Netherlands. Similar levels of investment to those in the Netherlands are required.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Good practice design guidance must be enforced to prevent wasteful implementati</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">on of poor quality schemes.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Investment in cycling must be prioritised to improve the health of the nation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">and,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> reduce congestion, pollution </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">and road</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> danger.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">The economic, health, transport and environmental benefits of increased cycling must be incorporate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">d in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">TfL</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> cost-benefit calculations.</span></li></ul></td></tr></table><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">10</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">. HGV DANGER</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">10.1 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">In London 9 out of 14 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">cycling fatalities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> in 2013 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">were</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> the result</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> of collisions with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">lorries</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">10.2 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">LCC has been in the forefront of the campaign to reduce danger from heavy goods vehicles</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> most recently with the Safer Lorries for Safer Cycling campaign targeting all London </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">boroughs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and the design of an urban lorry that significantly increases a driver’s direct vision. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">10.3 LCC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, advised by a transport expert and ex lorry driver, lobbied </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">uccessfully </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">the inclusion in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">TfL</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">contracts of a requ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">irement for lorry operators to:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.15pt; padding-left:8.55pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">be members of FORS (the Fleet Operators Recognition Scheme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> quality standard</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">); </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.15pt; padding-left:8.55pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">have vehicles with full safety features to detect cyclists and pedestrians; </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.15pt; padding-left:8.55pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ensure that all drivers have had their driving and criminal records checked; </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.15pt; padding-left:8.55pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> that they have completed Approved Driver Training</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> that includes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> a practical ‘on bike’ element.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">10.4 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">LCC shares the view of other cycling organisations that the volume of goods vehicles on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">urban </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">roads at busy times must be reduced </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">both </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">through traffic manage</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ment solutions and consolidation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> depots. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="background-color:#d9d9d9; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:462.1pt"><p style="margin:3pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">10.5 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Recommendations</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">All local authorities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">governm</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ent organisations, to adopt </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">similar </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">terms</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">TfL</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> procurement policy for freight operators</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> to drop un-necessary exemptions on lorry side-g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">uards (e.g. most refuse trucks) and to encourage </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">purchase </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">of urban lorries with good visibility</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:10pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 27.6pt; padding-left:8.4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Restrict</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> goods vehicl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">e numbers on urban roads at peak</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> times</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_GoBack"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">December 2012</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> 2011 national census</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> Attitudes to Cycling, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">Synovate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">TfL</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> 2009</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">ycling</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> demonstration</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> towns – an economic evaluation,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">Cycling England 2009 </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> Collection of Cycling Concepts 2012 , Cycling Embassy of Denmark </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> Dr Harry Rutter, who led the NICE study said: "Only a minority of people in England get enough physical activity to improve their h</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">ealth," "This creates a huge and often invisible burden of illness and reduced quality of life, but most people seem to be unaware of the scale of that burden. Across the population, lack of physical activity causes roughly the same level of ill-health as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">smoking does.”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> Vision for Cycling , Mayor of London 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn7"></a><a href="#_ftnref7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">Road Safety, second report of session 2012-2013, House of Commons </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">Transport Committee  2012</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn8"></a><a href="#_ftnref8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> Barriers to Cycling in London , London Councils 2008; Barriers to Cycling in Outer London, London Cou</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">ncils 2010</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn9"></a><a href="#_ftnref9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> Creating a Chain Reaction, The London Cycling Action Plan,  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">TfL</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> 2004</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn10"></a><a href="#_ftnref10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> 42,000 signatories to LCC petition calling for safer and more inviting streets</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn11"></a><a href="#_ftnref11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> Design Manual for Bicycle Traffic, CROW (Netherlands Information and Technology Platform)  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">2007</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn12"></a><a href="#_ftnref12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> Better Junctions Review  - ongoing - commenced in 2011</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn13"></a><a href="#_ftnref13">[13]</a><span sty